The key insights to solve this problem are:

1. Use the linearity property of the cross product to expand the left-hand side of the equation.
2. Recognize that $\bold{a} \times \bold{a} = \bold{b} \times \bold{b} = \bold{0}$ since the cross product of a vector with itself is always the zero vector.
3. Use the anticommutative property of the cross product, i.e., $\bold{b} \times \bold{a} = -\bold{a} \times \bold{b}$, to simplify the expression.
Step 1: Expand the left-hand side of the equation using the linearity of the cross product.
$$\begin{align*}
(5 \bold{a} + 7 \bold{b}) \times (-\bold{a} + 3 \bold{b}) &= -5 \bold{a} \times \bold{a} + 15 \bold{a} \times \bold{b} - 7 \bold{b} \times \bold{a} + 21 \bold{b} \times \bold{b}
\end{align*}$$

Step 2: Simplify the expression using the properties of the cross product.
$$\begin{align*}
-5 \bold{a} \times \bold{a} + 15 \bold{a} \times \bold{b} - 7 \bold{b} \times \bold{a} + 21 \bold{b} \times \bold{b} &= \bold{0} + 15 \bold{a} \times \bold{b} + 7 \bold{a} \times \bold{b} + \bold{0} \\
&= 22 \bold{a} \times \bold{b}
\end{align*}$$

The key insight in this solution is to use the fact that $13$ is a prime number, which implies that each of $a$, $b$, and $c$ has a multiplicative inverse modulo $13$. By introducing new variables $x$, $y$, and $z$ as the multiplicative inverses of $a$, $b$, and $c$ respectively, the problem can be simplified and solved using a system of linear congruences.
1. Let $a^{-1}=x$, $b^{-1}=y$, and $c^{-1}=z$ in modulo $13$.
2. Multiply both sides of each congruence by $(abc)^{-1}$ to obtain:
   $$\begin{align*}
   2z+x+y&\equiv 0 \pmod{13}\\
   z+2x+y&\equiv 6 \pmod{13}\\
   z+x+2y&\equiv 8 \pmod {13}
   \end{align*}$$
3. Add all three congruences together to get:
   $$\begin{align*}
   4(x+y+z)&\equiv 14\pmod {13}\\
   x+y+z&\equiv 10\pmod {13}
   \end{align*}$$
4. Subtract the result from step 3 from each of the congruences in step 2 to obtain:
   $$\begin{align*}
   z&\equiv -10\equiv 3\pmod{13}\\
   x&\equiv -4\equiv 9\pmod{13}\\
   y&\equiv -2\equiv 11\pmod {13}
   \end{align*}$$
5. Use the results from step 4 to find $a+b+c$ modulo $13$:
   $$\begin{align*}
   a+b+c&\equiv x^{-1}+y^{-1}+z^{-1}\pmod{13}\\
        &\equiv 9+3+6\pmod{13}\\
        &\equiv 18\equiv 5\pmod{13}
   \end{align*}$$
